User : Rotation of an array.
jarvis : To rotate an array, you can use the following steps:
1.  Decide the number of positions to rotate the array.
2.  Use a temporary array to store the rotated elements.
3.  Copy the last 'n' elements of the original array to the beginning of the temporary array, where 'n' is the number of positions to rotate.
4.  Copy the remaining elements of the original array to the end of the temporary array.
Here is a Java code snippet that demonstrates the rotation of an array:
```java
public class ArrayRotation {
    public static void rotateArray(int[] arr, int n) {
        int[] temp = new int[arr.length];
        int len = arr.length;
        // Copy the last 'n' elements to the beginning of the temporary array
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            temp[i] = arr[len - n + i];
        }
        // Copy the remaining elements to the end of the temporary array
        for (int i = n; i < len; i++) {
            temp[i] = arr[i - n];
        }
        // Copy the rotated array back to the original array
        for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
            arr[i] = temp[i];
        }
    }
    public static void printArray(int[] arr) {
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
            System.out.print(arr[i] + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
        int n = 2;  // Number of positions to rotate
        System.out.println("Original Array:");
        printArray(arr);
        rotateArray(arr, n);
        System.out.println("Rotated Array:");
        printArray(arr);
    }
}
```
This code rotates the array to the right by 'n' positions. For example, if the input array is `[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]` and `n = 2`, the output will be `[4, 5, 1, 2, 3]`.
You can also use Java's built-in `System.arraycopy()` method to simplify the rotation process:
```java
public class ArrayRotation {
    public static void rotateArray(int[] arr, int n) {
        int len = arr.length;
        n = n % len;  // Handle cases where 'n' is greater than the array length
        int[] temp = new int[n];
        System.arraycopy(arr, len - n, temp, 0, n);
        System.arraycopy(arr, 0, arr, n, len - n);
        System.arraycopy(temp, 0, arr, 0, n);
    }
    public static void printArray(int[] arr) {
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
            System.out.print(arr[i] + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
        int n = 2;  // Number of positions to rotate
        System.out.println("Original Array:");
        printArray(arr);
        rotateArray(arr, n);
        System.out.println("Rotated Array:");
        printArray(arr);
    }
}
```
This version of the code uses `System.arraycopy()` to copy the elements from one part of the array to another, which can be more efficient than using loops.
